ce:abstract-sec.ce:simple-para:
A new preparation approach for high density of carbide-oxide heterointerfaces was demonstrated. The resulting carbide-oxide heterostructured catalyst showed very high hydrogen evolution reaction (HER) activity compared to the state-of-the-art carbide-based HER catalysts. More importantly, the single-cell test using WO(3−

                        x

                     )−WCy/CDs as the cathode in polymer electrolyte membrane water electrolysis cell showed a current density of 10 mA cm−2 with a cell voltage of only 1.47 V, which is very close to that for Pt/C (1.41 V).

Carbide–oxide heterointerfaces have been known to be responsible for electrochemical activity, however, it is rarely investigated in tungsten carbide-oxide heterostructure for the hydrogen evolution reaction (HER). Furthermore, typical carbide preparation includes carbonization of oxide under gaseous carbon sources at a high temperature, resulting in sintering and collapse of the heterostructures. In this work, nano-sized carbon dots (CDs, ∼2 nm in diameter) were adopted as carbon sources and dispersed on tungsten oxide nanorods allowing abundant nucleation sites for oxide-to-carbide conversion, resulting in high density of carbide-oxide heterointerfaces. The resulting tungsten carbide-oxide heterostructure decorated with carbon dots (WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs) exhibited superior electrocatalytic activity toward the HER with a low overpotential of 65 mV at a current density of − 10 mA cm−2 in acidic media. This performance is among the best electrocatalytic activities compared to the state-of-the-art tungsten carbide-based electrocatalysts. Importantly, the single-cell test using WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs as the cathode showed a current density of 10 mA cm−2 with a cell voltage of only 1.47 V, which is very close to that for Pt/C (1.41 V). In addition, a combined analysis of the X-ray spectroscopic and electrochemical results suggested an optimal W–C ratio in the tungsten carbide-oxide composite to guarantee the high HER activity. Theoretical calculations provided more insight into the carbide-directed enhancement of the electrocatalytic activity of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs.

ce:section.ce:para:
For the synthesis of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs, 0.5 g tungstic acid (H2WO4, Sigma-Aldrich, 99 %) was dissolved in 20 mL of DI water and continuously stirred at 90 °C for 1 h. Then, 5 mL of H2O2 (Alfa Aesar, 30 wt%) was slowly dropped to the above aqueous solution under vigorous stirring. Subsequently, 115 μL of 1 M HCl (Alfa Aesar, 36–38 %) and 0.16 g Na2SO4 (Alfa Aesar, 99 %) were added to the above homogeneous solution. The light-yellow solution gradually turned into a colorless solution. Next, 20 mL of the as-prepared CDs solution (8 mg/mL) was added to the mixed solution and transferred to a Teflon-stainless steel autoclave, followed by heating at different temperatures (140 °C, 160 °C, 180 °C, or 200 °C) for different times (6, 12, or 24 h). The white solid products were collected by centrifugation several times with DI water and ethanol to remove large particles before drying at 60 °C in a vacuum oven. Finally, the as-synthesized products were placed in a quartz tube and calcined at 850 °C for 2 h at a ramp rate of 10 °C min−1 under an Ar atmosphere. Different annealing temperatures (800 °C, 850 °C, 900 °C, and 950 °C) were also applied for preparing comparison samples. For comparison, the mass ratio of H2WO4 to CDs was controlled to 1.2:1, 2.4:1, and 4.8:1 under optimized synthetic conditions (hydrothermal treatment at 180 °C for 12 h, followed by annealing at 850 °C for 2 h).

A membrane electrode assembly (MEA, 1 cm2) was prepared by spraying the catalyst ink directly onto a Nafion 115 membrane (Chemours Co). The cathode catalyst layer contained WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs with a ratio of ionomer to catalyst (0.2). The anode catalyst layer contained iridium oxide (IrO2, Alfa Aesar, 99.99 %) with the same ratio of ionomer to catalyst. The catalyst loading of each electrode was 1 mg·cm−2. MEA was assembled with carbon (SGL carbon, 39BC) gas diffusion layer at the cathode side and titanium (Bekaert, 2GDL6-025 N) gas diffusion layer at the anode side by hot-pressing at 130 °C for 2 min.

All investigations were performed using the density functional theory (DFT). The Perdew-Burke-Ernzerhof (PBE) functional of the generalized gradient approximation (GGA) [33] was used to describe the exchange and correlation energy of electrons in Quantum Espresso software [34]. The behavior of the core electrons was approximated using ultrasoft pseudopotentials [35]. The bulk WO3 structure was fully optimized using a non-shifted 9 × 9 × 9 k-mesh [36]. Energy cutoffs of 75 (50) Ry and 600 (400) Ry were used for the wavefunctions and charge density, respectively, for bulk (surface) calculations. A (3 × 3) supercell was used to avoid the interaction of oxygen vacancies and adsorbed hydrogen with their periodic images. The vacuum size was fixed at 15 Å. Ionic relaxation for all the surface calculations was performed using spin-polarized calculations with a 2 × 2 × 1 k-mesh for Brillouin zone (BZ) sampling. Self-consistent field (SCF) calculations were considered converged when the forces on each dimension and the total energy for ionic minimization were reached within the threshold of 10−5 (10−4) Ry and 10−4 (10−3) Ry, respectively [37], and criteria for a total energy convergence of 10−10 (10−7) Ry for bulk (surface) calculations. For hydrogen-adsorbed structures, we used DFT-D3[38]-type van der Waals (vdW) corrections to incorporate the vdW corrections into the total energy. The optimized lattice parameters (a = b = c = 3.83 Å) for bulk WO3 were found to be in agreement with the earlier studies (PDF # 04–5867). The surface structure used for HER was a (100)-terminated surface of the bulk WO3 structure, where oxygen coverage on the bottom surface was symmetric to that of the top layer [39]. The bottom three layers out of the five layers were kept fixed during ionic relaxation of the intermediate structures. To calculate the free energy profiles for HER, all the possible sites of hydrogen adsorption on the surface of WO(3-

                           δ

                        ) and WO{(3-

                           δ

                        )-

                           y

                        }C
                           y
                         (y = 1) were explored thoroughly, as shown in Fig. S24-25. XCrysden and VESTA software were used for crystal structure visualization [40,41].

Scheme S1 shows the facile synthesis process of the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composite. First, CDs were synthesized as a single carbon source from a mixture of glucose and uric acid. CDs containing abundant surface/edge sites can boost electron-coupling interactions between C−, N−, and O− components and W atoms [42,43]. Subsequently, the CDs were mixed with a tungsten precursor solution, and the mixture was hydrothermally treated in a Teflon-lined autoclave at various temperatures and times. The final WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composite was obtained by carbothermal reduction of the hydrothermally treated samples in an Ar atmosphere. The hydrothermal temperature and time have a significant influence on the final structure and electrochemical properties of the catalysts, as discussed in Section 3.2. Based on electrochemical analyses, it was found that the optimized hydrothermal temperature and time were 180 °C and 12 h, respectively.

The morphologies, structures, and sizes of the CDs, WO3−
x , and WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs were characterized by SEM and HRTEM (Fig. 1 and Fig. S1). The TEM images of CDs indicated that nanodots were well-dispersed without agglomeration with a mean diameter of 2.5–3 nm (Fig. S1a − c). The lattice fringe with an interlayer distance of 0.21 nm corresponds to the lattice spacing of the (100) crystal planes of graphitic carbon [29]. Fig. S1d depicts a uniform morphology of nanorod for WO3−
x . The lattice fringe of WO3−
x is 0.380 nm, which corresponds to the (100) plane of WO3 [44,45]. Contrarily, the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composite had a regular nanorod array morphology (Fig. 1a,b). The magnified TEM image shows that the nanorods consist of tungsten oxide nanorods connected with tungsten carbide on the surface (Fig. 1c). As shown in the HRTEM image, the nanorod has a polycrystalline structure consisting of nanocrystalline oxide and carbide, which are evenly distributed in the heterostructure. The lattice fringes with interplanar distances of 0.380 nm and 0.252 nm correspond to the (100) crystal planes of WO3 and WC, respectively [13,44]. Co-presence of the lattice fringes on the same nanorod indicates that the components are intimately contacted and, therefore, heterostructure has been successfully constructed. More importantly, carbide crystal domains on the oxide surface have very small sizes (few nanometers) allowing high density of oxide-carbide heterointerfaces. The reason why the CDs are not visible on the surface is that the size of CDs is very small (∼2 nm) compared to the nanorods (hundreds of nm). Since the tiny CDs cannot be clearly observed within the composite system, the exact location of the CDs cannot be identified. However, the presence of CDs in the composite was confirmed with the following X-ray spectroscopic characterizations. CDs dispersed on the surface are expected to play important roles: i) direct supply of a carbon source from nano-CDs intimately attached to the oxide surface initiating carbonization at the surface; ii) locally distributed CDs on the surface enable partial carbonization of the surface, increasing the number of heterointerfaces considered as electrochemically reactive sites, and iii) intimate contact between oxide and generated carbide facilitates charge transfer [46,47]. Furthermore, it was found that hydrothermal reaction conditions have a significant influence on the final structure and electrochemical properties of the catalyst. The SEM images (Figs. S2-S3) of the samples prepared under different hydrothermal reaction conditions show the morphology of the nanorod arrays similar to the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs prepared under optimized hydrothermal conditions (180 °C and 12 h, Fig. S2c). Particularly, the size and shape became uniform and clearer at 180 °C compared to those of the other temperatures. However, when the temperature was further increased to 200 °C, the particles were seriously agglomerated (Fig. S2d). In order to track the structural change after annealing, the catalyst precursor before annealing; CDs-distributed oxide nanorods was also characterized with XRD, SEM, and XPS as shown in Figs. S4–S5. Notably, XRD peaks for tungsten carbide were newly evolved after annealing, suggesting the successful fabrication of tungsten carbide on tungsten oxide surface in the presence of CDs (Fig. S4). The catalyst precursor before annealing has a uniform morphology of nanorods that are interlinked (Fig. S1d). The morphology was also well retained after the annealing as shown in the SEM image (Fig. S5a). W 4f XPS spectra clearly showed the evolution of tungsten carbide peaks after the annealing, supporting the XRD result (Fig. S5c).

XRD analysis was further used to investigate the crystalline structure and purity of the products. The XRD patterns of the CDs, WO3−
x , and WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs are shown in Fig. S6. For CDs, the diffraction peaks appeared at around 2θ of 26° and 42° are attributed to disordered carbon atoms of (002) and (100) planes for graphitic carbon [48], respectively, and match well with the interlayer d-spacing of the (100) planes observed in the HRTEM image (Fig. 1f). For WO3−
x , the XRD patterns are related to the reduced tungsten oxide standards (WO2.83 and WO2.95). The XRD patterns of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composites prepared under optimized hydrothermal condition (180 °C and 12 h) are consistent with the standard patterns of graphitic carbon, tungsten oxide, and tungsten carbide. This result is in good agreement with the TEM observations, which demonstrated the coexistence of WO3−
x , WC, and CDs in the composite. For the XRD patterns of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composites prepared at different hydrothermal temperatures (Fig. 2 a), a peak around 2θ of 26° was observed for all samples, which is ascribed to the (002) plane of graphitic carbon indicating the presence of CDs in the composites. At reaction temperatures below 180 °C, the peaks associated with tungsten oxide were more dominant than those of tungsten carbide. At 180 °C, the diffraction peaks from tungsten carbide are clearly observed with the disappearance of some peaks from tungsten oxide. However, when the hydrothermal temperature reached to 200 °C, the intensities of the representative tungsten carbide peaks decreased due to the decomposition of CDs at high temperatures resulting in a lack of C source required for carbonization. Additionally, the tungsten oxide also changes from cubic to hexagonal phase, which is considered to be less active for the HER [49]. Contrarily, the samples prepared with different hydrothermal reaction times under the same temperature of 180 °C were also studied and compared, as shown in Fig. S7. If the reaction time is less than 12 h, tungsten oxide becomes the main component of the composite because the reaction time is too short to induce interactions between the CDs and tungsten oxide. Contrastingly, when the reaction time was extended to 24 h, the peaks of tungsten carbide decreased because of further oxidation to h-WO3 due to prolonged exposure to reaction solution. In all cases, peaks arising from impurities other than oxides, carbides, and CDs were not observed.

XPS was implemented to gain more insight into the oxidation state and chemical composition. The XPS spectra of CDs, WO3−
x , and WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs are provided in Figs. S8–S10. The XPS spectra of the CDs indicate the presence of C, O, and N elements without impurities (Figs. S8 and S9). The XPS spectra of WO3−
x confirmed the presence of tungsten oxide with mixed oxidation states of W(VI) and W(V) (Figs. S8 and S10). The XPS spectra of the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composite demonstrate the coexistence of WO3, WC, and CDs in the composite. Fig. S11 and Fig. 2b−d show the XPS spectra of the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composites prepared at different hydrothermal temperatures. The deconvoluted W 4f XPS spectra showed two major doublets (Fig. 2b): an orange-colored doublet at 35.8 eV (4f7/2) and 37.9 eV (4f5/2), and a green-colored doublet at 34.4 eV (4f7/2) and 36.6 eV (4f5/2), which are indicative of W(VI) and W(V) species coming from tungsten oxide, respectively [50,51]. A purple-colored doublet at 31.2 eV (4f7/2) and 33.7 eV (4f5/2) is attributed to tungsten carbide [52,53]. The relative peak area for tungsten carbide increased at the expense of that for W(VI) as the reaction temperature increased to 180 °C (Table S1). This can be attributed to the reduction of W(VI) to W(V) with the formation of tungsten carbide. When the reaction temperature was increased to 200 °C, the peak area for tungsten carbide decreased owing to the decomposition of CDs, which caused the lack of a carbon source. The XPS peak parameters and quantified peak areas are described in Table S1-S4 of the SI.

The HER electrochemical performance was examined using a three-electrode cell in 0.5 M H2SO4. Fig. 3 a shows the LSV curves of the hydrothermal temperature-controlled WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs catalysts. A benchmark Pt/C catalyst was also tested for comparison. WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs prepared under optimal condition (hydrothermal treatment at 180 °C for 12 h) showed noticeable HER performance by generating a current density of − 10 mA cm−2 with an overpotential (η) of 65 mV, which is much lower than those of the samples prepared at 140 °C (523 mV), 160 °C (484 mV), and 200 °C (165 mV). As displayed in Fig. 3b, the Tafel slope for WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs prepared at 180 °C showed the lowest value of 50 mV dec−1 compared to other samples prepared at 140 °C (88 mV dec−1), 160 °C (68 mV dec−1), and 200 °C (57 mV dec−1). For all samples, electrochemical desorption is the rate-determining step, following the Volmer − Heyrovsky mechanism [57,58]. EIS measurements were conducted to investigate the charge-transfer kinetics during the HER. Fig. 3c shows the Nyquist plot measured at −0.6 V (vs. RHE). The fitting results of the series resistance (R s ) and charge-transfer resistance (R ct ) are summarized in Table S6. The charge-transfer resistance decreased in the following order: 140 °C > 160 °C > 200 °C > 180 °C, which is in agreement with the electrocatalytic activity trend observed in the LSV curves and Tafel plots. The HER activity of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs is superior to those of most electrocatalysts based on tungsten carbide or oxide reported thus far in terms of overpotential and Tafel slope, as summarized in Fig. 3d and Table S7.

To gain a better understanding of the origin of the electrocatalytic activity of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs, the double-layer capacitances (C dl) of the samples were calculated as they are deemed to be proportional to their electrochemically active surface area (ECSA). As shown in Figs. S14 and S15, and Table S5, the results indicated that WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs (180 °C) exhibited a larger ECSA than those of the other samples (140 °C, 160 °C, and 200 °C). To evaluate the intrinsic activity, the HER currents were normalized with the ECSAs. In the ECSA-normalized LSV curves (Fig. S16), the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs showed superior HER performance compared to the CDs, and WO3−
x . The result indicates that the enhancement in the intrinsic activity of WO3−
x originates from the synergistic effects between the oxide and carbide. However, we note that since the ECSA includes all electrochemically available sites, it is difficult to say that it is representative of the catalytically active interface only. In this regard, exchange current density (j0 ) was additionally calculated from the Tafel plot, as summarized in Table S5. Typically, j0 is proportional to the catalytically active surface area [59,60] and reflects the intrinsic activity of charge transfer between electrode and electrolyte. The exchange current densities of CDs, WO3−
x , and WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs are 9.59 × 10−7, 2.25 × 10−6, and 1.5 × 10−5, respectively, demonstrating that WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs heterostructure exhibits higher intrinsic activity, which lead to more favorable proton discharge [27,60]. Thus, the results imply that the heterointerface of carbide and oxide would be responsible for the high HER activity.

To evaluate the effect of W and C precursors ratio in the HER, comparison experiments were conducted with various precursor ratio. Fig. S17 shows the HER performances of the precursor ratio-controlled samples in 0.5 M H2SO4. The catalytic activity of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs with a mass ratio of H2WO4: CDs = 2.4: 1 was superior to those of the other samples. The results indicate that there is an optimal ratio of tungsten and carbon precursors for producing active heterostructure catalyst. The effect of the hydrothermal reaction time on the HER performance was also explored (Fig. S18). The catalyst fabricated with a reaction time of 12 h showed higher HER performance than those of the other samples (6 h and 24 h). A short reaction time (6 h) could not guarantee the sufficient reaction time required to form the optimal composite. An extended reaction time (24 h) could lead to further oxidation to inactive h-WO3 due to prolonged exposure to the reaction solution, which can degrade the HER performance. MATLAB simulation was used to summarize and simulate the optimal conditions for the hydrothermal process, as presented in Fig. S19.

Based on the above experimental results, WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs can be regarded as an effective catalyst for the HER. Especially, the enhanced catalytic activity of the composite has been observed to be closely related to the amount of tungsten carbide in the composite. Thus, to scrutinize the relationship between the WC x content and HER activities, WC x content-controlled composites were prepared by applying different annealing temperatures (800 – 950 °C) and their HER performances were compared. Quantifications of deconvoluted XPS spectra (Fig. S20a–c) showed the successful synthesis of composites with various WC x contents (3.11–7.23 % and 4.11–5.91 % calculated from the W 4f and C 1s XPS spectra, respectively).

A combined analysis of the XPS and electrochemical results established a relationship between the overpotential and WC x content (Fig. 4 ). There is an optimal WC x content (5.36–6.53 %) in the composite for the HER. Therefore, WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs composites should be synthesized to obtain optimal WC x content by modulating the synthesis conditions, while forming a rigid anchoring between the components to maximize the synergy between them.

Apart from the electrocatalytic activity, stability and durability are also essential parameters for evaluating the practical applicability of electrocatalysts. The electrochemical stability of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs was investigated using cyclic voltammetry (CV). As depicted in Fig. 5 a, the LSV curves showed no significant change even after 1000 CV cycles. Only a marginal increase in the overpotential from 66 to 74 mV at a current density of − 10 mA cm−2 was observed suggesting its high stability in acidic media. To investigate the structural changes after the stability test, XRD analysis was performed (Fig. S22a). The crystalline structure of WO(3-
x
)–WC y /CDs was well maintained after the test. As shown in Fig. S22b, the surface chemical structure was also examined by XPS after the test. The result reveals that its surface compositions almost remained with a tiny increase of the W6+ species, indicating slight surface oxidation during the HER operation (Table S8). Quantification of the peak area revealed that there was no distinct change in the WC x content after the long-term test. Furthermore, the morphology of WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs remained identical to the original morphology without any damage or aggregation of the structure, as confirmed by the SEM images (Fig. S23). The chronopotentiometry (CP) curve of the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs catalyst was studied at a current density of − 10 mA cm−2 for 24 h (Fig. 5b). The degradation of the current density after 24 h was negligible, which further demonstrated its robust durability. Consequently, these results suggest that WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs are promising HER catalysts with excellent activity as well as stability.

Even though WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs exhibit high HER performance in a half-cell, evaluation of single cell performance is more important from a practical point of view. Hence, the single-cell test was performed using a PEMWE cell by applying WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs as the cathode catalyst and IrO2 as the anode catalyst. The LSV curve of the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs catalyst is shown along with that of the 20 wt% Pt/C catalyst in Fig. 6 a. The WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs-based PEMWE achieved a current density of 10 mA cm−2 at a cell voltage of only 1.47 V, which is very close to that of Pt/C-based PEMWE (1.41 V). Additionally, the CP curve measured at a current density of 10 mA cm−2 exhibited a negligible change over 24 h operation (Fig. 6b). These results demonstrate that the WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs-based PEMWE is efficient and durable.

In summary, we have demonstrated WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs with abundant carbide–oxide heterointerfaces as an efficient and durable electrocatalyst for the HER. The WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs heterostructure exhibits outstanding electrocatalytic activity toward the HER (overpotential of 65 mV at − 10 mA cm−2 with a Tafel slope of 50 mV dec−1), which is superior to those of the tungsten carbide-based HER catalyst. The enhanced HER performance is attributed to i) high density of electrochemical active sites coming from the abundant carbide-oxide heterointerfaces, ii) synergy between three components (tungsten oxide, tungsten carbide, and CDs, and iii) facilitated charge transfer by intimate contact between the three components. Additionally, DFT calculations supported the experimental result that incorporation of carbide in tungsten oxide can enhance the HER performance. A combined analysis of the spectroscopic and electrochemical results revealed a volcano-relation between HER activity and catalyst composition, which suggested an optimal carbide content in the composite. Furthermore, the single-cell test with WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs as the cathode catalyst showed a very low cell voltage of 1.47 V at a current density of 10 mA cm−2, which is very close to that for Pt/C (1.41 V), demonstrating its practical applicability to commercial PEMWE. This finding reveals that WO(3−
x
) − WC y /CDs is a promising non-precious HER catalyst that can compete with current platinum-based electrocatalyst and provides a rational guideline for designing active HER catalysts. Inspired by the finding, in the near future, there is a plan to investigate the effect of heterointerface and related mechanisms with more elaborately designed catalysts.
